{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646632"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:33:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:33:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18195"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18195"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.03,0.09,0.15,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79345"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10909"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18195"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64666"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7173"},{"type":"tags","id":"10333"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25363"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25366"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79345"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with numbness along the lateral border of her foot and sole, including her fourth and fifth toes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following intervertebral disc levels would most likely cause these symptoms if herniated?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["S1-S2","L2-L3","L3-L4","L4-L5","L5-S1"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003EL5-S1\u003C/strong\u003E. A disc herniation at this level typically compresses the S1 nerve root as it exits the spinal canal. The S1 dermatome includes the posterolateral calf and lateral aspect of the foot, including the lateral two toes and part of the sole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ES1-S2\u003C/strong\u003E - This is below the level where clinically significant disc herniations occur\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL2-L3\u003C/strong\u003E - A herniation at this level affects the L3 nerve root, which supplies the anterior and lateral thigh\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL3-L4\u003C/strong\u003E - This level affects the L4 nerve root, which supplies the anteromedial leg and medial foot\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL4-L5\u003C/strong\u003E - This level affects the L5 nerve root, which supplies the lateral leg and dorsum of the foot\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe relationship between spinal nerve roots and their dermatomes follows a predictable pattern that is crucial for localising neurological lesions. The S1 nerve root commonly becomes compressed with L5-S1 disc herniations, producing characteristic sensory symptoms in its dermatome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The S1 nerve root is responsible for sensation in the plantar aspect of the foot, including the lateral two toes.","A disc herniation at the L5-S1 level can compress the S1 nerve root as it exits the spinal canal.","The S1 dermatome includes the posterolateral calf and lateral foot including the small toe."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64666"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18195"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64666"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T10:15:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T10:16:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10909"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79345"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I",